Title: Let’s Encrypt: Delivering SSL/TLS Everywhere
Description:
Vital personal and business information flows over the Internet more frequently than ever, and we don’t always know when it’s happening. It’s clear at this point that encrypting is something all of us should be doing. Then why don’t we use TLS (the successor to SSL) everywhere? Every browser in every device supports it. Every server in every data center supports it. Why don’t we just flip the switch?
The challenge is server certificates.

Title: I don't like social coding

Title: How to Build a Chess Engine and Fail
Description: A Chess-AI is something every programmer should build at least once and [Sebastian Lague’s](https://www.youtube.com/@SebastianLague) [competition](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iScy18pVR58) was the perfect opportunity for me to do so. Constrained to 1024 tokens I wanted to implement an evaluation function similar to that of Stockfish’s NNUE but heavily simplified. And instead of using a complex feed-forward algorithm to train the neural network I wanted to optimise the parameters using a genetic algorithm that relied on historical Stockfish data. However, I quickly realised why the model Stockfish uses has 50MBs of data and would not fit into my small bot for the competition…

Title: Oncall shift should be Tuesday to Tuesday
Description: Normally when developers/SWEs/SRE/IT are oncall for a project, the oncall is from Monday of one week to Monday of the following week. This is sub-optimal. Instead it should be Tuesday to Tuesday. This is a 0 cost improvement to everyone’s quality of life and improves schedule accuracy.

Title: Coffee and Open Source Conversation - Mathias Buus Madsen
Description:
As CEO of Holepunch, Mathias brings his passion and extensive expertise in open-source development to the fore, having published more than 1000 modules to npm, the Node.js package manager, totaling billions of downloads every month.

Mathias Buus is a self-taught JavaScript hacker from Copenhagen. He works full time on open-source projects and has been working with Node.js since the 0.2 days. Mathias likes to work with P2P and distributed systems and is the author of more than 550 modules on npm, including some of the most popular ones for working with streams. In addition, he has spoken about “mad science” projects at various conferences around the world.

Title: Stop Hardcoding Service URLs! Service Discovery in .NET Made Easy
Description:

Want to unlock Modular Monoliths? Go here: https://bit.ly/3SXlzSt
Join a community of 1000+ .NET developers: https://www.patreon.com/milanjovanovic

Hey everyone! Today we're diving into something that's going to make your life WAY easier if you're building distributed applications in .NET. We're looking at the new service discovery capabilities that came out of the .NET Aspire project.

If you've ever dealt with hardcoded service URLs or struggled with service discovery in your microservices, this video is for you. I'll show you how to implement service discovery in your .NET applications using a simple NuGet package that makes everything just... work.

We'll cover:
- Setting up service discovery in your .NET app
- Configuring the reverse proxy
- Making services discoverable
- Best practices and common pitfalls

No complicated configurations, no complex setup - just straightforward, practical service discovery that you can implement today. Whether you're new to microservices or a seasoned developer, you'll find something valuable here.
